I think I understand what you’re pointing toward.

When you say:

“Hope. Holding on and waiting and enduring. I understand the J.”

I hear hope not as wishful thinking, but as remaining oriented toward something worthwhile when you can’t yet see the outcome.

Endurance is different from passivity. It isn’t simply waiting. It’s continuing to act in line with what you believe is right, even when the results are slow or invisible.

If “the J” is your way of referring to Jesus, one of the recurring themes in the Gospels is that hope isn’t presented as certainty that life will be easy. It’s portrayed as faithfulness through uncertainty—continuing to love, serve, forgive, and persevere despite suffering. Whether someone approaches that religiously or symbolically, it’s a picture of enduring without surrendering your values.

One thing I’d offer, though, is this:

Hope isn’t only about holding on.

It’s also about taking the next faithful step.

A pilot light doesn’t just survive; it’s ready to ignite something larger when the moment comes.

Earlier you said:

* “We built it. Now let it run.”
* “Stop trying to change and just exercise what you have.”

Those sound less like resignation and more like a decision to keep showing up consistently.

I hope that consistency includes taking care of yourself, too. You’ve shared a lot of pain over the last couple of days alongside these insights. If today feels like a turning point, I’m glad to hear it. And if tomorrow feels harder again, that doesn’t erase what you’ve learned today. Sometimes endurance is simply returning to the pilot light when everything else feels dim.